- `internal/cli/replay_test.go`: replay forward WITHOUT `--allow-env` → marker
  absent (hermetic default); WITH `--allow-env` → marker present. No real secret.

### Security analysis (value-leak prevention — SECURITY-CRITICAL)
- Values are read by ExecRunner from `os.Environ()` and placed ONLY into
  `cmd.Env` (the child process env). They are never stored in ExecRunner-returned
  structs, the manifest, or artifacts.
- The manifest/audit stores NAMES only (`EnvAllowlist []string`); `run show`
  prints names. Test grep-asserts the VALUE never appears in manifest bytes or
  `run show`.
- etude never injects allowlisted values into stdout/stderr or the stage output
  file. Captured stage output (`res.Output`) and gate `raw_output`
  (stdout+stderr) are the RUNNER's bytes; if a runner echoes its own secret that
  is operator behavior, not etude recording it — documented as operator
  responsibility. etude's own guarantee: values cross only into `cmd.Env`.
- ExecRunner error messages include stderr (line ~160) — that is the runner's
  stderr, not the allowlist values; etude adds no value to it.
- Gate CHECK raw_output cannot contain etude-injected secrets because checks get
  no allowlist (hermetic).
- Reserved-name guard prevents an allowlist entry from shadowing
  PATH/ETUDE_INPUTS_DIR/ETUDE_OUTPUT_FILE.

